{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17657797","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17657797"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:35:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:35:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20649"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20649","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20649"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.72,0,0.16,0,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13525"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96894"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13525","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13525"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20649"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79509"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"10955"},{"type":"tags","id":"11585"},{"type":"tags","id":"11789"},{"type":"tags","id":"12536"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32300"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32301"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96894","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96894"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents with chest discomfort and breathing difficulties. Cardiac imaging shows fluid around the heart. Examination of pericardial tissue reveals a pink-staining network of strands in the pericardial cavity.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the underlying pathological process in this patient\u0027s pericardium?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Leakage of fibrinogen with conversion to fibrin","Aggregation of lymphocytes and plasma cells","Growth of fibroblasts with matrix production","Precipitation of calcium compounds in injured tissue","Gathering of neutrophils within the tissue"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient has fibrinous pericarditis, characterized by \u003Cstrong\u003Eleakage of fibrinogen with conversion to fibrin\u003C/strong\u003E. This occurs when blood vessel permeability markedly increases during inflammation, enabling large proteins such as fibrinogen to escape into the extracellular environment. The fibrinogen subsequently transforms into fibrin, which microscopically appears as a pink-staining network of strands or as a shapeless clot.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAggregation of lymphocytes and plasma cells\u003C/strong\u003E - This pattern is typical of chronic inflammatory responses, not the acute fibrinous process described\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGrowth of fibroblasts with matrix production\u003C/strong\u003E - This represents the organization phase, a later stage where persistent fibrinous exudates trigger fibroblast migration and scarring\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrecipitation of calcium compounds in injured tissue\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes dystrophic calcification, an unrelated pathological process\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGathering of neutrophils within the tissue\u003C/strong\u003E - While neutrophils may be present during acute inflammation, the distinctive feature described is fibrin deposition, not neutrophil infiltration\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFibrinous exudates commonly develop on serosal surfaces lining body cavities including the pericardium, pleura, and meninges. If not eliminated through fibrinolysis and phagocytosis, the fibrinous exudate may eventually undergo organization, resulting in fibrous thickening and potential adhesions in the pericardial space.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["During inflammation, increased vascular permeability allows fibrinogen to escape into tissues where it forms fibrin deposits in extracellular spaces.","Fibrinous exudates typically develop on body cavity linings including the meninges, pericardium, and pleura.","If not resolved, fibrinous exudates may undergo organization through fibroblast proliferation and angiogenesis, resulting in scarring."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 3, Inflammation and Repair; p. 93-94"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79509"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20649"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79509","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79509"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-03T12:21:33+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-03T12:22:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13525"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96894"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"10955","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10955"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Acute inflammation","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-11-27T10:23:38+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-27T10:23:38+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"10"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type"